ed both from the north and the south. Focusing on political ideologies, a number of important issues are raised relating to the medieval state, the signification of the nation under the ‘Ancien Regime’, the role of warfare in the creation of political power and the impact of political loyalties in the exercise of government. In doing so, the book challenges a number of existing ideas about the Burgundian state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBurgundian State.  aCharles the Bold.  aFeudal State.  aFeudal loyalties.  aGeographical Knowledge.  aLow Countries.  aMedieval Majesty.  aNational identity.  aPolitical communication.  aPolitical communities.1 aFletcher, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLecuppre-Desjardin, Élodie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packagez978311128144540uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614434840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526144348423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526144348/original  a978-3-11-128144-5  Manchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packageb2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles